Mapping FTICR Data to MetaCyc

Amanda White

2019-02-11

Source: vignettes/mapping_to_metacyc.Rmd
mapping_to_metacyc.Rmd

Some introduction here about why we’d want to do this.

MetaCyc is a database of metabolic pathways: https://metacyc.org. Reference: Caspi et al 2018, “The MetaCyc database of metabolic pathways and enzymes”, Nucleic Acids Research 46(D1):D633-D639

PNNL has created an R package of data from MetaCyc, which is available here: https://github.com/EMSL-Computing/MetaCycData. It can be installed with the command:

devtools::install_github("EMSL-Computing/MetaCycData")

The first step is to map the peak ICR data to compounds in MetaCyc. This is done by comparing the molecular formula assignments for each peak to compound molecular formulas from the database. Not all peaks will have molecular formulas, and many molecular formulas will map to multiple compounds.

library(fticRanalysis)
library(MetaCycData)

data("peakIcrProcessed")

compoundData <- mapPeaksToCompounds(peakIcrProcessed, db="MetaCyc")
#> Warning in mapPeaksToCompounds(peakIcrProcessed, db = "MetaCyc"): Multiple
#> masses map to the same molecular formula/compound. Constructing a unique ID
#> for e_data.

The db parameter specifies what database use; currently “MetaCyc” is the only valid option, but in the future other databases may be added. (And “MetaCyc” is the default so it does not have to be specified.)

Notice that a warning message is printed; this is because multiple peaks in the original data are assigned the same molecular formula. This is not uncommon but could create a problem for downstream analysis unless it’s resolved. The function combinePeaksWithSameFormula will perform this operation by adding the abundance values of rows with the same molecular formula (or for presence/absence data, ‘or’-ing the rows).

peak2 <- combinePeaksWithSameFormula(peakIcrProcessed)
#> 313 mass formulas with duplicate values found
summary(peak2)
#> Samples: 20
#> Molecules: 8114
#> Percent Missing: 57.408%
#> Group Sizes:
#>  M_S : 5 
#>  M_C : 5 
#>  W_C : 5 
#>  W_S : 5
compoundData <- mapPeaksToCompounds(peak2, db="MetaCyc")
summary(compoundData)
#> Samples: 20
#> Molecules: 488
#> Percent Missing: 28.740%
#> Group Sizes:
#>  M_S : 5 
#>  M_C : 5 
#>  W_C : 5 
#>  W_S : 5

Notice how many fewer rows of data there are in compoundData versus peak2. This is due to the fact that so few peaks have molecular formulas assigned. The compound ID is stored in the e_meta table in the Compound column:

head(compoundData$e_meta[, c("Mass", "Compound")])
#>          Mass                              Compound
#> 1 203.0925331 DIETHYL-2R3R-2-METHYL-3-HYDROXYSUCCIN
#> 2 205.0142391                             CPD-16467
#> 3 207.0299141                             CPD-21613
#> 4 209.0091827                             CPD0-2184
#> 5 209.0091827                             CPD-11853
#> 6 209.0455619                             CPD-18045

These IDs can be used to map back to the MetaCycData package (the mc_compounds data.table contains compound information). This information includes the URL and common name among other fields.

dplyr::filter(mc_compounds, COMPOUND=="CPD-16467")
#>    COMPOUND                                                        URL
#> 1 CPD-16467 http://metacyc.ai.sri.com/compound?orgid=META&id=CPD-16467
#>                       COMMON-NAME MONOISOTOPIC-MW MOLECULAR-WEIGHT      MF
#> 1 3-[(1-carboxyvinyl)oxy]benzoate        208.0372          206.154 C10H6O5
#>     CHEMICAL-FORMULA
#> 1 (C 10) (H 6) (O 5)
#>                                                                                                  DBLINKS
#> 1 (PUBCHEM "25767865" NIL |kothari| 3619399262 NIL NIL) (CHEBI "76981" NIL |kothari| 3608052289 NIL NIL)

Once compounds have been identified, the data can then be mapped to reactions and/or modules (pathways). For mapping to reactions and modules, working with presence/absence data makes more sense,

compoundData2 <- edata_transform(compoundData, "pres")

rxnData <- mapCompoundsToReactions(compoundData2)

Since compounds and reactions have a many to many relationship, the number of rows in e_data is different from that of compoundData2. The columns of e_meta have also changed. Previous metadata that was applicable to peaks and compounds is not applicable to reactions. Instead, there are four columns:

  • Reaction: database ID
  • EC_Number: Enzyme Commission number
  • Compounds_in_Dataset: semi-colon delimited string of which compounds in the source dataset were mapped to the reaction
  • N_Observable_Compounds: number of compounds in the database which could have been observed, subject to any mass filters previously applied to the source dataset

The proportion of compounds observed per reaction can be calculated by parsing the Compounds_in_Dataset field and dividing its element-wise length by the value in N_Observable_Compounds.

n_cmp_observed <- unlist(lapply(strsplit(rxnData$e_meta$Compounds_in_Dataset, ";"), length))
prop_cmp_observed <- n_cmp_observed/rxnData$e_meta$N_Observable_Compounds

We could also look at which reactions are observed in different treatment groups, using divideByGroupComparisons and sumamrizeGroupComparisons. When mapping from peaks to compounds, reactions or modules, group definition information is carried along in the resulting data objects, so the groups defined in peakIcrProcessed based on Location and Crop.Flora are available in rxnData.

rxnGroupCompData <- divideByGroupComparisons(rxnData, comparisons="all")

rxnCompSummary <- summarizeGroupComparisons(rxnGroupCompData, summary_functions = "uniqueness_gtest",
                                            summary_function_params=list(uniqueness_gtest=
                                                                           list(pres_fn="nsamps", pres_thresh=2,
                                                                           pvalue_thresh=0.5)))
